      "index": "b33",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 928064706,
      "version": 1437,
      "versionNonce": 1999009828,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1784569281509,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. My first solution is i think bubble sort? anyways what i am going to do is an in-place sort. becuase we aren't allowed to use extra space. The approach goes like this\nfirst i would just bubble up the smaller of the two number i would be comparing and do this for each pair of element as i go along the array. and after finishing the first iteration i would\ndo the same thing again a total of n-1 times when n is the number of elements in the array. and that should sort it after i have tried it myself but can i prove it that it will always sort the array\nAnother approach which i believe is the actual bubble sort is that i would go to the element in question and as long as the element before is not smaller than it i would continue to bubble it up and doing \nthis for all element in the array would definitely make the array sorted and i can see why that is true. but again can i prove it?\nWell what I did was both variants of the bubble sort and it works.  I know this because the definite way of proving algorithms i leant it its just loop invariants base case maintainance and termination. just a little bit of induction \nand voila we got our proof of any algorithm from now on.\n",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. My first solution is i think bubble sort? anyways what i am going to do is an in-place sort. becuase we aren't allowed to use extra space. The approach goes like this\nfirst i would just bubble up the smaller of the two number i would be comparing and do this for each pair of element as i go along the array. and after finishing the first iteration i would\ndo the same thing again a total of n-1 times when n is the number of elements in the array. and that should sort it after i have tried it myself but can i prove it that it will always sort the array\nAnother approach which i believe is the actual bubble sort is that i would go to the element in question and as long as the element before is not smaller than it i would continue to bubble it up and doing \nthis for all element in the array would definitely make the array sorted and i can see why that is true. but again can i prove it?\nWell what I did was both variants of the bubble sort and it works.  I know this because the definite way of proving algorithms i leant it its just loop invariants base case maintainance and termination. just a little bit of induction \nand voila we got our proof of any algorithm from now on.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "QXSr8hh8XKA-VbuVHVj9p",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2800.804001878855,
      "y": -1473.9287324711527,
      "width": 22195.708984375,
      "height": 1085,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#6741d9",
