      "updated": 1784569152998,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Although i know i am constrained to do it in constant space i though about this another way of solving. so if i have duplicate element of a number of finite elements whose ordering we know we can just easily know how the sorted array will look. \nlike we can just maintain a constant lookup hashmap of the element and the end index till which we are storing this. offcourse for the smallest element of the unique elements of that array it will start from 0 index in the sorted array, and so we can by its end index know where to start\nthe next greatest element. so instead of sorting the given array we only ever sort the unique elements and maintain a hashmap of those elements to later populate a new array. to make this hashmap we will iterate over the given input ofintegers and whenever we get the smallest element we will add 1 to its index and also to all other's greater than it. \nalso in the hashmap the end index of the next greater element is assigned to be 1 greater than its previous element. and general rule it when we get an element we increase the end index of it and all element greater than it in our hashmap and then. using these end indices we can i think hopefull initialize an array using somebuilt in function to populate aan intereger\nfrom a given index to another. this approach seems to work but can i prove it? atleast will get this approach ratified from AI first. Ok so i leant that since we know the elements are going to be 0,1and 2 Ai said we don't even need to track the end points with a map or something\nJust going over the array once we can count stuff and based on that count we can comeback to edit the same input array again effectively sorting it so this is like I invented the COUNTING SORT, yipeee we win i guess.\n",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Although i know i am constrained to do it in constant space i though about this another way of solving. so if i have duplicate element of a number of finite elements whose ordering we know we can just easily know how the sorted array will look. \nlike we can just maintain a constant lookup hashmap of the element and the end index till which we are storing this. offcourse for the smallest element of the unique elements of that array it will start from 0 index in the sorted array, and so we can by its end index know where to start\nthe next greatest element. so instead of sorting the given array we only ever sort the unique elements and maintain a hashmap of those elements to later populate a new array. to make this hashmap we will iterate over the given input ofintegers and whenever we get the smallest element we will add 1 to its index and also to all other's greater than it. \nalso in the hashmap the end index of the next greater element is assigned to be 1 greater than its previous element. and general rule it when we get an element we increase the end index of it and all element greater than it in our hashmap and then. using these end indices we can i think hopefull initialize an array using somebuilt in function to populate aan intereger\nfrom a given index to another. this approach seems to work but can i prove it? atleast will get this approach ratified from AI first. Ok so i leant that since we know the elements are going to be 0,1and 2 Ai said we don't even need to track the end points with a map or something\nJust going over the array once we can count stuff and based on that count we can comeback to edit the same input array again effectively sorting it so this is like I invented the COUNTING SORT, yipeee we win i guess.\n",
