      "updated": 1784573820912,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "I am here and back again! \nI learnt that the optimal way to solve it in a single pass is using the Dutch National flag Algorithm by the Dijkstra person he invented this.\nbasically we keep pointers. well who would have thought? well me becuase we keep 3 pointers, one for the tracking of the zero's indices another for tracking of the 2s indices and 1 as our current pointer\nwhen we encounter 0 we just swap the value at the current zero pointer and increase the zero pointer and move on by increasing the current pointer. When we have a value of 2 at the current pointer we just swap it with \nthe value present at the 2's pointer we then decrement the two's pointer( to bring it closer to the middle) but we don't increase our current pointer because we must check what value we've got from the unknown 2's region\nso that if  it's a zero we may swap it out again for the value at the zero's pointer and then move on or if it's a one well just do nothing. for all 1's we just do nothing. by sorting out the 0s and 2s we automatically sort out the 1s as well\nand at the end of a single pass we just get out answer. but i am thinking whether if we had more than 3 could we have sorted it then. i would like like to believe this same algorithm would definitely work for just two types of integers as well right\nSo i have got news. this dutch pointer approaach doesn't work for more than 3 types of input in the array. Anyways congratulations for solving the problem i guess;",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "I am here and back again! \nI learnt that the optimal way to solve it in a single pass is using the Dutch National flag Algorithm by the Dijkstra person he invented this.\nbasically we keep pointers. well who would have thought? well me becuase we keep 3 pointers, one for the tracking of the zero's indices another for tracking of the 2s indices and 1 as our current pointer\nwhen we encounter 0 we just swap the value at the current zero pointer and increase the zero pointer and move on by increasing the current pointer. When we have a value of 2 at the current pointer we just swap it with \nthe value present at the 2's pointer we then decrement the two's pointer( to bring it closer to the middle) but we don't increase our current pointer because we must check what value we've got from the unknown 2's region\nso that if  it's a zero we may swap it out again for the value at the zero's pointer and then move on or if it's a one well just do nothing. for all 1's we just do nothing. by sorting out the 0s and 2s we automatically sort out the 1s as well\nand at the end of a single pass we just get out answer. but i am thinking whether if we had more than 3 could we have sorted it then. i would like like to believe this same algorithm would definitely work for just two types of integers as well right\nSo i have got news. this dutch pointer approaach doesn't work for more than 3 types of input in the array. Anyways congratulations for solving the problem i guess;",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
